{"title_page": "Albert Elsen", "text_new": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Albert Edward Elsen\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = 1927\n| birth_place = [[New York City]]\n| death_date = February 2, 1995\n| death_place = [[Stanford, California]]\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Columbia University]]\n| employer = [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation = Art historian\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = Patricia Morgan Kline<br/>Sharon McClenahan Elsen\n| children = 1 son, 2 daughters\n| parents = \n| relatives = \n}}\n'''Albert Edward Elsen''' (1927 - February 2, 1995) was an American art historian. He was a professor at [[Stanford University]], and the author of several books about [[Auguste Rodin]].\n\n==Early life==\nElsen was born in 1927 in New York City.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Roberta |title=Albert Elsen, 67, Art Historian And an Authority on Rodin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/08/obituaries/albert-elsen-67-art-historian-and-an-authority-on-rodin.html |accessdate=December 3, 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=February 8, 1995}}</ref> He earned a BA, MA and PhD from [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\n==Career==\nElsen taught Art History at [[Carleton College]] from 1952 to 1958, and at [[Indiana University]] for the next decade.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/> He became a professor at Stanford University in 1968.<ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite news |title=Albert Elsen; Stanford Professor, Rodin Expert |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/158977317/?terms=%22Albert%2BElsen%22 |accessdate=December 4, 2018 |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=February 5, 1995|page=A22|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> He encouraged [[B. Gerald Cantor]], the chairman of [[Cantor Fitzgerald]], to establish the Rodin Sculpture Garden on campus.<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\nElsen authored several books, most notably about sculptor [[Auguste Rodin]]. According to the ''Baltimore Sun'', Elsen was \"credited with reviving public and scholarly awareness of Rodin's work.\"<ref name=\"baltimoresunobit\">{{cite news |title=Albert Elsen |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/171271838/?terms=%22Albert%2BElsen%22 |accessdate=December 4, 2018 |work=The Baltimore Sun |date=February 6, 1995|page=54|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> Other books authored by Elsen were about abstract expressionist painters [[Paul Jenkins (painter)|Paul Jenkins]] and [[Seymour Lipton]], as well as about [[Henri Matisse]].<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nElsen was married twice. He divorced his first wife, Patricia Morgan Kline, and subsequently married Sharon McClenahan Elsen. He had a son and two daughters, and he resided in Stanford, California.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\nElsen died of a heart attack on February 2, 1995 in Stanford.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/><ref name=\"baltimoresunobit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elsen, Albert}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Carleton College faculty]]\n[[Category:Indiana University faculty]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:American art historians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n\n\n{{US-art-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Albert Edward Elsen\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = 1927\n| birth_place = [[New York City]]\n| death_date = February 2, 1995\n| death_place = [[Stanford, California]]\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Columbia University]]\n| employer = [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation = Art historian\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = Patricia Morgan Kline<br/>Sharon McClenahan Elsen\n| children = 1 son, 2 daughters\n| parents = \n| relatives = \n}}\n'''Albert Edward Elsen''' (1927 - February 2, 1995) was an American art historian. He was a professor at [[Stanford University]], and the author of several books about [[Auguste Rodin]].\n\n==Early life==\nElsen was born in 1927 in New York City.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Roberta |title=Albert Elsen, 67, Art Historian And an Authority on Rodin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/08/obituaries/albert-elsen-67-art-historian-and-an-authority-on-rodin.html |accessdate=December 3, 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=February 8, 1995}}</ref> He earned a BA, MA and PhD from [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\n==Career==\nElsen taught Art History at [[Carleton College]] from 1952 to 1958, and at [[Indiana University]] for the next decade.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/> He became a professor at Stanford University in 1968.<ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite news |title=Albert Elsen; Stanford Professor, Rodin Expert |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/158977317/?terms=%22Albert%2BElsen%22 |accessdate=December 4, 2018 |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=February 5, 1995|page=A22|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> He encouraged [[B. Gerald Cantor]], the chairman of [[Cantor Fitzgerald]], to establish the Rodin Sculpture Garden on campus.<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\nElsen authored several books, most notably about sculptor [[Auguste Rodin]]. According to the ''Baltimore Sun'', Elsen was \"credited with reviving public and scholarly awareness of Rodin's work.\"<ref name=\"baltimoresunobit\">{{cite news |title=Albert Elsen |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/171271838/?terms=%22Albert%2BElsen%22 |accessdate=December 4, 2018 |work=The Baltimore Sun |date=February 6, 1995|page=54|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> Other books authored by Elsen were about abstract expressionist painters [[Paul Jenkins (painter)|Paul Jenkins]] and [[Seymour Lipton]], as well as about [[Henri Matisse]].<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nElsen was married twice. He divorced his first wife, Patricia Morgan Kline, and subsequently married Sharon McClenahan Elsen. He had a son and two daughters, and he resided in Stanford, California.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\nElsen died of a heart attack on February 2, 1995 in Stanford.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/><ref name=\"baltimoresunobit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elsen, Albert}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Carleton College faculty]]\n[[Category:Indiana University faculty]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:American art historians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n\n{{US-art-historian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Elsen"}
